04647nam a22007695i 9780231541176DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015018086  a(OCoLC)979628958  a97802315411767 a10.7312/dalt176002doi  a(DE-B1597)473098  a(OCoLC)946724465  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBQ7662.4b.D35 2016 7aREL0070202bisacsh04a294.3/4382231 aDalton, Jacob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Gathering of Intentions :bA History of a Tibetan Tantra /cJacob Dalton. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Origins: Myth and History -- t2. The Gathering of Intentions in Early Tibetan Tantra -- t3. The Spoken Teachings -- t4. The Rise of the Sutra Initiation -- t5. Dorjé Drak and the Formation of a New Lineage -- t6. The Mindröling Tradition -- t7. Returns to the Origin -- tAppendix: The Four Root Tantras of Anuyoga -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Gathering of Intentions reads a single Tibetan Buddhist ritual system through the movements of Tibetan history, revealing the social and material dimensions of an ostensibly timeless tradition. By subjecting tantric practice to historical analysis, the book offers new insight into the origins of Tibetan Buddhism, the formation of its canons, the emergence of new lineages and ceremonies, and modern efforts to revitalize the religion by returning to its mythic origins.The ritual system explored in this volume is based on the Gathering of Intentions Sutra, the fundamental "root tantra" of the Anuyoga class of teachings belonging to the Nyingma ("Ancient") school of Tibetan Buddhism. Proceeding chronologically from the ninth century to the present, each chapter features a Tibetan author negotiating a perceived gap between the original root text—the Gathering of Intentions—and the lived religious or political concerns of his day. These ongoing tensions underscore the significance of Tibet's elaborate esoteric ritual systems, which have persisted for centuries, evolving in response to historical conditions. Rather than overlook practice in favor of philosophical concerns, this volume prioritizes Tibetan Buddhism's ritual systems for a richer portrait of the tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aRnying-ma-pa (Sect)xRituals. 0aRñiṅ-ma-pa (Sect)xRituals. 0aSpiritual lifexRnying-ma-pa (Sect) 0aSpiritual lifexRnying-ma-pa (Sect). 0aSpiritual lifexRñiṅ-ma-pa (Sect). 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2016z9783110485394oZDB-23-DGF40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/dalt1760040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231541176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231541176/original  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGFb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016